# Commits (Devmoji + Conventional Commits)

When the user asks you to **create git commits**, use this format for every commit subject line:

```text
type(scope): <emoji> <subject>
```

- **Types:** `feat`, `fix`, `docs`, `style`, `refactor`, `perf`, `test`, `build`, `ci`, `chore`
- **Scope:** optional, lowercase area (`deps`, `access`, `i18n`, `design-system`, `docker`, `agents`, `app`, …)
- **Emoji:** Unicode gitmoji/Devmoji symbol immediately after `: ` (e.g. `✨` `🐛` `♻️` `📄` `✅` `🔧` `⬆️` `💄` `🌐` `🐳`)
- **Subject:** imperative, concise; explain *why* in the body when the change is non-obvious

Full reference and examples: [`docs/COMMITS.md`](../../docs/COMMITS.md).

## Examples

```text
feat(i18n): 🌐 wire Payload custom translations for runtime and config
refactor(access): ♻️ modularize access control and collection policies
chore(deps): ⬆️ bump Payload, Next, Bun, and lockfile
docs(app): 📄 add conventions, testing guide, and agent overlay
```

## Multi-commit work

Split by logical area (deps, agents, config, access, tests, design-system, frontend, i18n, docs, docker) — one Devmoji subject per commit unless the user wants a single commit.

## Do not

- Use plain `fix: something` without an emoji when committing in this repo
- Use `npm`/`npx` in commit instructions (Bun only — see `bun.mdc`)
- Run `git commit --no-verify` unless the user explicitly requests skipping hooks
- Add **`Co-authored-by:`** (or similar) trailers naming AI agents, bots, or tools (Cursor, Copilot, Claude, ChatGPT, etc.) — commits attribute **human authors only** unless the user explicitly asks for a specific co-author
